[[table]]
[[row]]
[[hcell]]
[[div class="blockquote"]]
[[div style="text-align: center !important"]]
//[...]//
[[/div]]

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] I'm still baffled at what you were able to accomplish. The rubberband effect would have lasted at least another... well, it could have lasted ten years without you beavering away in there. Maybe longer. I couldn't... we couldn't have waited that long. We needed you back, and here you are.

[[span class="at"]]Chief Torosyan-Deering:[[/span]] Yeah. Here I am.

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] How did you keep perspective? How did you keep on working to that goal, without any foreknowledge that you had a chance?

[[span class="at"]]Chief Torosyan-Deering:[[/span]] That's always been the job. We don't take snow days.

= //<Dr. Deering laughs. Chief Torosyan-Deering looks away again.>//

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] I'm sorry. I'm just relieved.

= //<Chief Torosyan-Deering looks back again.>//

[[span class="at"]]Chief Torosyan-Deering:[[/span]] Yeah, I know you are. That's not the problem.

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] What is?

[[span class="at"]]Chief Torosyan-Deering:[[/span]] It's just... I've never heard you laugh like that before.

[[span class="dd"]]Dr. Deering:[[/span]] Like what?

[[span class="at"]]Chief Torosyan-Deering:[[/span]] Like... him.

[[div style="text-align: center !important"]]
//[...]//
[[/div]]
[[/div]]
[[/hcell]]
[[/row]]
[[/table]]

@@ @@

[[div class="notation at"]]
Phil, my imaginary Phil, used to tell me I was right or wrong based on what I thought he'd think. I knew him like a glove, it was a near-perfect simulation; the gulf between that and reality was the first permanent pit in my stomach. But still, it was a comfort. My apparition of Dougall Deering? All he could say was that I was right, and he was sorry.

He's always so damn sorry.
[[/div]]

@@ @@

